snippet.textDisplay: One of the worst scenes (in my opinion) was the scene where Tyler tells Clay about the abuse. Someting very traumatic happened to him and the way he directly talks about it just seems kind of strange. He talks about the assault for the first time and just discribes what happened in so much detail and almost without pause. If you know just a little bit about the way trauma works you know that he most likely would not act like this. When trauma happens the brain seperates the event from the emotions the victim feels and because of that I don't think it is realistic for him to cry and be so emotional about it in that scene. I guess the directors of the show just wanted the scene to be very emotional and/or didn't do enough research on the topic. I am no therapist and I just know about this from personal experience, but the scene just made me mad. If anyond has a different opinion or just knows better, feel free to correct me on this. Also english is not my first language.

snippet.textDisplay:
I disagree with Bryce's transformation being out of left field. Granted, it may be more because of Justin Prentice's performance rather than the writing, but even back in Season 1, despite knowing Bryce was a monster, I liked him. He always seemed to be a good dude at heart but he just kept doing messed up things (and understatement, I know). He at least always seemed self hating. It's hard to make a case for this, sure. But there was always something about his demeanor. The way he seemed to agree with his mom when she called him a disgrace. The way he welcomed Clay into his home under the impression he was there to buy weed. The way he allowed Clay to threaten his life with a gun without an ounce of retaliation. Bottom line, Bryce's "shift" in Season 3 made sense to me.

I read the book way before I saw the show. I didn’t like the even the first season of show. Also the show is just inaccurate in so many ways. The show makes it seem like Hannah is blaming people for her death when in reality in the book the tapes were an explanation (it also explains how it wasn’t any one thing), not her trying to blame them.

I watched 13 Reasons Why Season 3 and I couldn't get into it. I watched the first two seasons and they were good, despite their flaws, but I couldn't complete the third season. Usually I don't mind sex scenes, but they felt too gratuitous in this season. Did I really need to see those horrible scenes with Alex Standall visiting a hooker and Monty get a blowjob from a pretty boy at a party? I mean I am really not homophobic but both of these scenes were disgusting! I cannot get their facial expressions out of my head!! And the thought of Ani sleeping with a nasty piece of shit like Justin, despite knowing full well what he has done.... Why would she do that?!!! What is wrong with the girl?!! Ugh... this season was just so disappointing....



Ghost Justin.... really?!!
